x4freetext: 12 MeV
One target was made by evaporating natural boron from a
tantalum strip onto a tantalum backing which was 1.9 cm
diam. and 0.13 cm thick.
The other target was an electromagnetically separated
target of 11B obtained from the Atomic Energy Research
Establishment, Harwell, England. The 11B was deposited
on a 2x2 cm tantalum backing that was 0.013 cm thick.
The thickness of the natural boron target was
determined to be 275+-50 ug/cm2 and the 11B (Harwell)
target to be 187+-34 ug/cm2.
For neutrons. The neutron spectrometer
was of the recoil telescope type. A single Argon-CO2
filled proportional dE/dx counter was used between
the radiator and a thin-crystal proportional counter.
Radiators were used of three different thicknesses:
in the 1-5 MeV deuteron range, 15 mg/cm2 to 45 cm2
thick and above 5 MeV, 30 mg/cm2 to 60 mg/cm2).
In order to resolve four neutron groups (n0 to n3) two
radiators were used at given energy and angle.
For deuterons. 0.25 cm thick, 2.5 cm in
diam., coved on the sides and in front face with
0.0013 cm thick Al foil.
